When editing merge changes in the git control panel when you edit the stash vs. updated upstream changes, if you remove code in the updated/stash code then undo and redo the changes there will be a red/orange bar on the code line that you edited. After than line of code is in orange/red bar you can only remove it by closing the file and reopening it.

Example:

```
var example = function () {
<<<<<<< Updated upstream           (this is a red/orange line)
    var updated;
=======                            (this is a red/orange line)
    var stashed;
>>>>>>> Stashed changes            (this is a red/orange line)
}
```

Then remove the git stashed/updated lines:

```
var example = function () {
    var stashed;
}
```

Then undo the changes:

```
var example = function () {
<<<<<<< Updated upstream           (this is a red/orange line)
    var updated;
=======                            (this is a red/orange line)
    var stashed;
>>>>>>> Stashed changes            (this is a red/orange line)
}
```

Then redo the changes, there will be a red/orange line: 

```
var example = function () {        (this is a red/orange line)
    var stashed;
}
```

Then the only way you can remove that red/orange line is to close the file you're editing and reopen it.

